Data Extraction¶

Leveraging Spotify API + Genius Lyrics¶

Spotify actually keeps a lot of data on songs internally, which we can access through the Spotify API. The data I am most interested in for this project is Spotify's numerical data. This includes:

  • popularity
  • danceability
  • loudness
  • speechness
  • acousticness
  • instrumentalness
  • valence
  • tempo
  • duration_ms

To get our lyrics, we will acess the LyricsGenius API. In order to make such requests for both API versions, we will need a client_id and a client_secret that you'll use to identify your machine to respective servers.

Step 0: Install Libraries¶

Below are the necessary library packages to conenct to the Spotify and LyricsGenius APIs. If you do not have these dependencies already isntalled, try: "conda install package_name" or "pip install package_name" if you are using Jupyter Notebook.

These unique tokens will allow for streamless connection to Spotipy. Below is the code necessary to capture connection with Spotipy. For privacy purposes, I will not disclose my developer tokens.

Step 2: Scraping Data from Both APIs¶

Extracting Tracks From a Playlist¶

The method that I will use to extract features from Tyler's tracks will be performed by the "playlist_tracks" method. This method uses a system of uniform resource identifers (URIs), which point at each object (the songs contained in our playlist) within the API, and ouputs JSON data containing all the of information about this playlist. Fortunately, the Spotipy library does this for us! To perform this, I compiled all of Tyler's albums into a single playlist. Spotify then generates a playlist_link. The method below will now extract the URI for each song in the playlist link that I provide it.

In [ ]:
playlist_link = "https://open.spotify.com/playlist/1pWfaOrtN2rVKJNEk1WfQ0?si=f043404188e34f65"
playlist_URI = playlist_link.split("/")[-1].split("?")[0]
track_uris = [x["track"]["uri"] for x in sp.playlist_tracks(playlist_URI)["items"]]

Now that we have a list of track URIs, we can scrape the features from these tracks and then their lyrics from the LyricsGenius API. We can access the audio features with a single method of the Spotify object audio_features(uri). We can extract song lyrics in tandem with both the Spotify and Genius objects with the following method below:

In [ ]:
song = LyricsGenius.search_song(artist_name, track["track"]["name"])
lyrics = song.lyrics

Note, that track["track"]["name"] is a method under the Spotify object. My method for collecting each songs' audio features is demonstrated below.

                 'speechiness', 'acousticness','instrumentalness', 'liveness',
                 'valence', 'tempo', 'duration_ms')
features = list(dict([(key, d[key]) for key in f]).keys())
In [ ]:
# extract data for each song in playist
for idx, track in enumerate(sp.playlist_tracks(playlist_URI)["items"]):
    c=0
    d['song'].append(track["track"]["name"])
    d['album'].append(track["track"]["album"]["name"])
    d['popularity'].append(track["track"]["popularity"])
    try:
        song = LyricsGenius.search_song('Tyler, The Creator', track["track"]["name"])
        d['lyrics'].append(song.lyrics)
        c+=1
    except:
        d['lyrics'].append(np.nan)
        print(f"some exception at {song}: {c}")
    for feature in features:
        d[feature].append(sp.audio_features(track_uris)[idx][feature])

Data Cleaning¶

There actually isn't a whole lot of cleaning we need to perform, but if you peak at some of the lyrics, there is unecessary text that is in between parentheses or brakcets that we can get rid of!

In [102]:
def clean_lyrics(l):
    """
    Removes text inside brackets and other special characters that are 
    unecessary to textual analysis
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    l : str
    Any piece of text 
    """
    l = re.sub(r'[\(\[].*?[\)\]]', '', l)
    l = re.sub(r'([0-9]+)(Embed)', '', l)
    # there were a few inconsistencies in how lyrics were extracted
    if 'Lyrics' in l:
        # start string from first instance of a linebreak to remove song titles
        start = l.find("\n")
        l = l[start:]
    l = l.replace('\n', ' ')
    l = l.replace('\r', '')
    return l

In [109]:
def facet_hist(groups, data, m_rows, m_cols, col, figsize, **kwargs):
    """
    Creates faceted histograms such that there is a seperate axis and 
    histogram for each group from a dataset
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    groups : ndarray
        1D array containing data with 'int' type between 0 and 1
    data : ndarray
        2D array containg data with 'float' type as a function of groups 
        plus gausian noise (bell curve)
    m_rows : int
        the number of desired rows in your faceted histogram
    m_cols : int
        the number of desired columns in your faceted histogram
    figsize : the size of the figure
        
    """
    if m_rows*m_cols == len(set(groups)): # check that rows & cols are configurable with amount of groups
        fig, axarr = plt.subplots(nrows = m_rows, ncols = m_cols, figsize = figsize) # set up plot(s)
        ix = 0 # free variable for group titles 
        vals = list(set(groups)) # list of unqiue values in data
        #ordering = [0, 4, 3, 2, 5, 1]
        #vals = [vals[i] for i in ordering]
        vals = list(dict.fromkeys(groups))
        for i in range(m_cols): 
            for j in range(m_rows):
                mask = groups == vals[ix] # mask group corresponding to value
                axarr[j, i].hist(data[mask], bins = 8, **kwargs) # plot histogram with data corresponding to True indices returned by mask
                axarr[j, i].set_title('{}'.format(vals[ix])) # title based off free variable
                axarr[j, 0].set_ylabel('Frequency') # y-label
                axarr[m_rows - 1, i].set_xlabel(col) # x-label
                fig.suptitle(f'Feature: {col}')
                ix += 1 # increment free variable
        plt.tight_layout() # ensures plots aren't squish
    else:
        raise ValueError('Value of n_groups in create_data() not configurable with function') # error if n_rows and m_cols not configurable with amount of groups

LexicalRichness¶

Lexical richness is commonly defined by the quality of vocabulary used in a single corpus or piece of text by linguistics. By some, this is interpreted as the variety of lexis, or in another words, simply the diversity of words. There are many ways to describe this phenomenon analytically, but one of the most popular indexes used is called the type-token ratio (TTR), where the type of word is divided by how many instances of that word appear in said corpus. Fortunately, we don't need to write too much code to implement this formula since we can import the LexicalRichness package (which has already been done). This library has a method called Measure of Textual Lexical Diversity, denoted as mtld, which we will use to apply this idea.

To get a better feel for Tyler's sentiment, I am interested in learning about his usage of explicit words. To do this, I am going to import the profanity package, which checks whether a lexicon is explicit or not.

In [128]:
from better_profanity import profanity
In [129]:
def count_dirty(x):
    """
    Return the amount of explicit words in a given text
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    x : str, any textual piece
    
    Returns
    ------
    count : int, the amount of explicit words in a piece of text
    """
    words = LexicalRichness(x).wordlist
    count=0
    for word in words:
        if profanity.contains_profanity(word):
            count+=1
    return count

def scatterplot_matrix(cols, figsize):
    """
    produces a scatterplot matrix 
    cols : str
        list of strings, each of which correspond to column names from the happiness dataset
    figsize : tuple
        desired figure size of each plot in scatterplot matrix
    
    """
    fig, axarr=plt.subplots(nrows = len(cols), ncols = len(cols), figsize = figsize) # set up plot
    for i in range(len(cols)): # nested for-loop so that each that there is a plot for each possible pairs of variables
        for j in range(len(cols)):
            if i == j: # condition so that diagonal is empty for each variable
                axarr[j, i].set_title('{}'.format(cols[j]), fontsize = 10)
                axarr[j, i].set_ylabel('{}'.format(cols[i]))
            else:
                axarr[j, i].scatter(df[cols[j]], df[cols[i]]) # produce scatter plot
                axarr[j, i].set_title('{}'.format(cols[j]), fontsize = 10) # title corresponding to each instance of pairing variable
                my_number = np.corrcoef(df[cols[j]], df[cols[i]].to_numpy())[0][1] # correlation coefficient
                axarr[j, i].set(xlabel = r"$\rho$ = " + str(np.round(my_number, 2))) # set correlation coefficient to x-axis label
                axarr[j, i].set_ylabel('{}'.format(cols[i])) # variable being compared to all other instance variables
                fig.suptitle('Associations of Target Variables')
    plt.tight_layout()
In [451]:
scatterplot_matrix(["lex_rich", "num_words", "valence", "popularity", "dirty_words", "acousticness"], figsize = (10,10))

  • as the number of words per song drop, acousticness increases
  • lexical richness and valence have a modest positive correlation
  • the number of words used per song has a strong positive correlation with the usage of explicit words
  • acousticness and usage of explicit words also has an inverse relationship

# Pearson Correlation Coefficient
for i in avg_album.columns.drop('album'):
    pearson = np.corrcoef(corpus_df["lex_rich"], avg_album[i])[1][0]
    abs_pearson = abs(pearson)
    description = str()
    if abs_pearson >= 0 and abs_pearson < 0.20:
        decscription = '(very weak)'
    elif abs_pearson >= 0.20 and abs_pearson < 0.40:
        description = '(weak)'
    elif abs_pearson >= 0.40 and abs_pearson < 0.60:
        description = '(moderate)'
    elif abs_pearson >= 0.60 and abs_pearson < 0.80:
        description = '(strong)'
    else:
        description = '(very strong)'
    print(i, ": ", pearson, description)

Topic Modeling¶

The overall goal of topic modeling is to find "topics" in corpuses of text by grouping words together that provide an abstract overview. Our overall aim for this section is to get a topic-level summary of each of Tyler's albums overtime. Our methods will include substantiating a term-document matrix in combination with awesome algorithms provided by sklearn.

Just think of the term-document matrix as a dataframe with a column for every possible word that exists in a piece of corpus. In each column, there exists a number that corresponds to how many times that lexicon appears in a subset of text.

Fortunately, our friends at sklearn provides us with a convenient solution!

To begin, we are going to grab the CountVectorizer function from sklearn.feature_extraction.text. This module will give us a whole range of functionality when converting our textual data into quantitative numbers that we can feed our NLP machine learning algorithms.

Next, we are going to create a CountVectorizer object, which we will create a term-document matrix for us. This object accepts a whole range of parameters, but we are going to focus in on max_df and stop_words. Because I would like to to eventually see how Tyler's lyrical topics evolve between each album, I use the max_df argument to specify that I'd like to include words that appear in at least 50% of the albums. Our stop_words parameter will include words that we previously defined that we consider uninteresting for the purposes of natural language processing.

Perfect, since topic modeling is considered unsupervised learning and thus we do not need a Y target variable, all we did was substantiate our predictor variables X produced by our term-document matrix. To do that, we ignored the columns corpus, lex_rich, album, tot_words, and avg_dirty.

Now for the most exciting part!

There are many types of topic modeling algorithms, but for our case we will use nonnegative matrix factorization (NMF). I won't go into the mathematical jargon of how NMF works, but in essence, NMF relies on linear algebra to decompose term-matrix documents into topics.

In essence, we start with some arbitrary matrix X defined by its documents (rows) and words (columns). Then we factor X into how many documents x topics we have multiplied by the number of topics x words exist in our matrix X. In other words, before the factorization we look at how often each word (a lexicon from each song lyric) appears in each document (or album). Subsequently, we then look at how strongly a topic is associated with each document.

Awesome, now we have a very surface-level understanding of how NMFs work (no problem!). Our NMF function insists that we specify n_components, which is the number of topics to find. Choosing the number of topics is sort of arbitrary, but let's choose 3 to see if there's any unique pattern of overlap between albums.

In [84]:
from sklearn.decomposition import NMF
model = NMF(n_components=3, init = "random", random_state = 0)
model.fit(X)
Out[84]:
NMF(init='random', n_components=3, random_state=0)

Now that we fit our model to our data, we have two import pieces to break down. We have the number of components, which we can think of as a collection of weights for each word defined by seperate rows. In our case, we rows 0, 1, 2. This is stored in our components_ attribute of our model. Basically, these weights within each row correspond to how important a word is in each component or topic that our model has found.

def top_words(X, model, component, num_words):
    """
    returns the most important words by topic in descending order
    """
    orders = np.argsort(model.components_, axis = 1)
    import_words=np.array(X.columns)[orders]
    return import_words[component][-num_words:]

Sentinment Analysis¶

Time for our most exciting part! Now that we have a good feel of Tyler's evolution on a very abstract level, let's attempt to classify the progression of positiveness of the artist soley based on his lyrics. As mentioned previously, Spotify actually keeps track of this feature in terms of valence, so in the end, we'll compare how our sentinment analyzer stacks up against Spotify's algorithm.

To peform this analysis, we are going to import the very handy SentinmentIntensity Analyzer using VADER. This classifier has been used widely on social media coprus, but let's see how it performs on Tyler's data! You can read more about its application here.

In [147]:

After creating an object of SentimentIntensityAnalyzer, we can create two seperate functions that will return 1) a sentiment score of the song lyrics and 2) classify the score as either Positive, Neutral, or Negative. The two functions that I created below will provide us with this ability.

In [169]:
def sentiment_score_percent(l):
    try:
        sentiment_score = analyzer.polarity_scores(l)
        sentiment_percentage = sentiment_score['compound']
            
    except:
        sentinment_percentage = np.nan
    
    return sentiment_percentage
In [175]:
def sentiment_score(l):
    try:
        sentiment_score = analyzer.polarity_scores(l)
        
        if sentiment_score['compound'] >= 0.05:
            sentiment = 'Positive'
        elif sentiment_score['compound'] > -0.05 and sentiment_score['compound'] < 0.05:
            sentiment = 'Neutral'
        elif sentiment_score['compound'] <= -0.05:
            sentiment = 'Negative'
    except:
        sentiment = np.nan
    
    return sentiment

General Discussion¶

By breaking down the evolution of Tyler based of his lyrics and converting it into juicy textual data, we can observe some awesome trends as an artist. From once a punk-ish, radical, and angry lyricist, Tyler has demonstrated his unqiue ability to transform himself into a more nuanced and refined song-writer, producer, and performer with an emphasis on the sound and story he tells through his work. He might have fewer things to say demonstrated by the decrease in lexical richness overtime, but I interpret this as Tyler's way of maturing and spreading a more positive outlook on life that deviates away from his youthful start in the industry.
